{      Game-Try ("Maximal") Doubles    }
^-|ht|d|fp||at|^B@2Suppose the auction begins: |ht|e|
cs|6|at|^b{|ia|1S2H2S3H?|at|}|ht|g|at|^iYou, the Opener are holding:|ht|d|at|^p|ih|pSA Q J 9 8 7H2DK J 2C7 6 5|ht|c|cs||at|^lExample 1|hf|j|lb|*bWhat should you make?^^x|ht|e|
cs|6|at|^b{|ia|1S2H2S3H!X|at|}|
ht|i|at|^B@2Because your side has 9 trumps, the LAW of Total Tricks |CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.larryco.com/BridgeArticles/ArticleDetails.aspx?articleID=229 ^*N|CP||AT| tells you to compete to the 3-level. You want to compete to 3@S. However, you don't want partner to think you are inviting game. For this kind of auction, the Game-Try double is a valuable tool:|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|

When your side has raised 1-MAJOR to 2-MAJOR, and the opponents interfere with the suit below your major on the 3-level, opener's double is a game try. It is not for penalty.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


AT| Meanwhile, opener's rebid of 3-MAJOR is competitive'to play. So, in this auction 3@S, as you see above, is ^*BTo play^*N.|
ht|e|cs|6|cp||at|^b{|ia|1S2H2S3H!3s|at|}|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


ht|p|va|4|cp||at|^B@2Note: This double is only when Opener's RHO bids the suit directly under the major. (So, the only other situation would be if your side started 1@H-2@H and Opener's RHO bid 3@D).

It doesn't matter how Opener's RHO came to make that bid in the suit below, but when there is no room for any other kind of game try, opener has to be able to bid 3-of-his-major to compete for the partial, while also having available a double to try for game opposite a maximum raise. This agreement can also be used if you start with an overcall (1-of-a-Major) and partner raises you to 2 of your major.|
