qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{          2. Support Double          }
^-|ht|c|cs||fp||va|4|cp|8|AT|^b@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|Since this is the most-forgotten convention on Earth, let me lead into it with a review of the two easier-to-remember doubles: the Takeout and Negative double. |
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


AT|

A Takeout Double is made when RHO opens the bidding and you double.|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


AT|

A Negative double is made when Partner opens the bidding, the opponents overcall, and you (the responder) double.|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


AT|

^*BA Support Double^*N is made when you open the bidding, partner responds, and you double the opponents. Note: ^*BIt is the opening bidder that makes aSupport Double.^*N|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


at|

Below is the prototype Support Double auction:|
ht|m|at|^bOPENER  ^fOPPONENT ^jRESPONDER ^nOPPONENT|ht|n|at|^b 1 Grape  ^f Anything  ^j 1 Orange ^n Some bid|ht|o|at|^b ^*BDouble^*N|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


AT|

Opener's double is a ^*Bsupport double^*N. It shows 3-card support for Responder's suit. It says nothing about HCP. So, if opener has:|
HT|r|at|^b|ih|pSA 4 3H6 5DK Q J 6 5CK 3 2|ht|r|at|^mHe makes a support double in this auction:|ht|s|cs|6|at|^m{|ia|1dp1S2cX|at|}|ht|x|at|^B@2The Double simply announces any opening bid with exactly 3-card spade support. If Opener has extra strength, he can divulge it later. If Opener eschews a Support Double and instead raises to 2S, it promises 4-card support.|
