qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{          Comment by Howard Schutzman          }
^-|ht|c|cs||fp||va|6|AT|Here is Howard's feeling about maximal doubles. They are a nice convention but can be confusing if not well understood. In particular, you have to understand they only apply over 3@D when your suit is hearts and over 3@H when your suit is spades. Thus, for example, on the auction 1@S-2@D-2@S-3@D-dbl, the double is not maximal. Note that 3@S over 3@D is still a competitive bid, not a game try. You can make a game try  over 3@D by bidding 3@H. As to whether you should play them or not. I tried them and no longer play them with many of my expert partners. I don't particularly miss them. If you want to play them, I think that is fine. But I don't think you should go out of your way to play them, especially with partners who tend to forget conventions or are easily confused.|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


AT|

Here is Howard's feeling about support doubles. They are useful and help in Law of Total Tricks calculations since they differentiate between 3-card support and 4-card support. But you have to understand when they apply. They  can only be made by opener after responder has bid a new suit at the 1-level. And they can only be made when responder' is only promising a 4-card suit. So, for example, if the auction goes 1@C-P-1@S-2@H-dbl, that is a support double showing 3-card support in spades. Responder is only promising 4 spades. But if the auction goes 1@C-1@H-1@S-2@H-dbl, that is not a support double. Responder has promised a 5-card spade suit. Similarly if it goes 1@D-1@H-2@C-2@H-dbl, that is not a support double. The 2@C bid is not at the 1-level and it also promises a 5-card suit. So, bottom line is, if you understand when a double is a support double, they can be useful. I slightly favor playing them. But again, if you are playing with a partner who tends to forget conventions, I suggest you don't play them.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


AT|

As to Cohen's contention that "all doubles at the 1-level and 2-level are not penalty", I don't agree with that. In particular, I have been very successful in match points at doubling opponents at the 2-level vulnerable. Beating them 1 for +200 is usually a top board. I have found that, because the modern style is to compete vigorously, opponents often get overly aggressive and bid poor 4-card suits at the 2-level when they should not. When I have length and strength in their suit, I am very willing to double them. So if a double is not takeout, negative, support, or responsive (assuming you play responsive doubles), assume it is penalty even at the 1-level and 2-level. Having said that, I will say that most experts agree with Cohen.|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


